recordings.loc: Great Britain, Braunston, Northamptonshire, England
recordings.rmk:
Recording is continuous but in two sections (I edited out one episode of impact and wind noise in the middle)

Bird singing from some height (5-6m) in a small piece of deciduous woodland near to pasture and water, close to a village. It's well concealed by foliage, and doesn't seem to move around much from one perch for some time.

I have noticed this song for lengthy periods (1 hour +) every morning for 2-3 weeks i.e. since around beginning of June 2020.
The song struck me as somewhat like Sylvia atricapilla, but some of the bursts consist of one or two slight variants of a very distinctive ** 3-note ** melody, which I don't associate with Sylvia atricapilla. The recording begins with a 3-note burst of this kind (at 0:00, and 00:57). Other bursts of the song seem to utilise the same three notes but in a less ordered arrangement along with other notes (e.g. at 0:22); or else the same three notes only, but with a different rhythm and slightly decorated by a short trill.
